<bill id="DLM1360800" in.amend="false" irdnumbering="no" official="yes" xml:lang="en-NZ" year.imprint="2009" bill.no="59" bill.type="government" stage="2" year="2009">
  <billdetail>
    <title>Student Loan Scheme (Exemptions and Miscellaneous Provisions) Amendment Bill</title>
    <billtype>Government Bill</billtype>
    <repnote>As reported from the Education and Science Committee</repnote>
    <commentary id="DLM2586000" in.amend="false" irdnumbering="no" official="yes" bill.no="59" bill.type="government" stage="2" year="2009">
      <heading>Commentary</heading>
      <comm.lev1>
        <heading>Recommendation</heading>
        <para>
          <text>The Education and Science Committee has examined the Student Loan Scheme (Exemptions and Miscellaneous Provisions) Amendment Bill and recommends by majority that it be passed with the amendments shown.</text>
        </para>
      </comm.lev1>
      <comm.lev1>
        <heading>Introduction</heading>
        <para>
          <text>This bill would amend the Student Loan Scheme Act 1992, by introducing two additional exemptions to the rule that borrowers are required to be present in New Zealand for 183 or more consecutive days to qualify for an interest-free loan. It would also make two technical amendments to the exemptions provisions in the Act, and a number of minor or technical amendments.</text>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>The additional exemptions would apply to borrowers who were not in New Zealand but were still in the Realm of New Zealand (that is, in Niue, the Cook Islands, Tokelau, or the Ross Dependency), and to borrowers engaged in full-time study overseas either under a New Zealand Government-approved formal exchange programme or under a formal agreement between a New Zealand tertiary education provider and an overseas tertiary provider. The technical amendments would affect the definition of the countries a borrower could work in to obtain the benefit of the volunteer exemption, and would clarify that a borrower could only obtain the benefit of this exemption if the organisation for which the borrower was working was a <quote.in quote="1">named</quote.in> organisation at the time the borrower did that work.</text>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>Three amendments would make other policy changes. The Commissioner of Inland Revenue would be allowed to increase the standard rate of repayment deductions from 10 to 15 cents in the dollar where borrowers had failed to have correct deductions made or failed to pay any other due amount. Loans that were fully repaid before the borrower had been back in New Zealand for 183 days would be interest-free for the period the borrower was back in New Zealand. The grace period in which a borrower may repay their loan fully without incurring further interest would be increased from 15 to 30 days.</text>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>Three other technical amendments are proposed. The period for which borrowers may seek relief on hardship grounds would no longer be limited to the tax year immediately preceding the current tax year. The formula for determining the student loan interest rate would be moved from the Student Loan Scheme (Interest Rates Formulas) Regulations 2006 to the principal Act. World-wide income in an income-contingent assessment would be limited to the period for which a borrower was entitled to an interest-free loan.</text>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>We note the assurance of the Inland Revenue Department that it has decided that assessments that were not issued in earlier years because of a computer programming error will not now be issued and the proposed increase repayment deduction rate would not therefore apply to borrowers affected by this error.</text>
        </para>
      </comm.lev1>
      <comm.lev1>
        <heading>Overseas study exemption</heading>
        <para>
          <text>We recommend amending clause 14, new section 38AJA. This would extend the overseas study exemption to include borrowers engaged in full-time study overseas where their New Zealand tertiary education provider verified that the study could not be completed in New Zealand, and would count towards a New Zealand qualification at level eight or above on the New Zealand Register of Quality Assured Qualifications; and would define an overseas tertiary provider.</text>
        </para>
      </comm.lev1>
      <comm.lev1>
        <heading>Green Party minority view</heading>
        <para>
          <text>The Green Party is unable to support this bill despite the laudable clauses which allow students from the Pacific and the Ross Dependency to access their tertiary education in this country without additional penalties. However we oppose the clauses which increase the amounts students in arrears will have taken from their earnings, the increase being from 10 cents in the dollar to 15 cents in the dollar.</text>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>The Green Party believes the student loan scheme is already a heavy burden on many students on low incomes and students who do not get high-paying jobs after they leave university. We oppose all initiatives which increase that burden. So despite the useful technical amendments in this bill we stand upon our principles in opposition to any increases in the rate of repayment on those already in arrears.</text>
        </para>
      </comm.lev1>
      <comm.appendix>
        <heading>Appendix</heading>
        <comm.lev2>
          <heading>Committee process</heading>
          <para>
            <text>The Student Loan Scheme (Exemptions and Miscellaneous Provisions) Amendment Bill was referred to the committee on 25 August 2009. The closing date for submissions was 2 October 2009. We received and considered five submissions from interested groups and individuals. We heard two submissions.</text>
          </para>
          <para>
            <text>We received advice from the Inland Revenue Department and the Ministry of Education.</text>
          </para>
        </comm.lev2>
        <comm.lev2>
          <heading>Committee membership</heading>
          <para>
            <text>Allan Peachey (Chairperson)</text>
          </para>
          <para>
            <text>Catherine Delahunty</text>
          </para>
          <para>
            <text>Hon Sir Roger Douglas</text>
          </para>
          <para>
            <text>Jo Goodhew</text>
          </para>
          <para>
            <text>Colin King</text>
          </para>
          <para>
            <text>Hon Nanaia Mahuta (from 6 May 2009 to 18 November 2009)</text>
          </para>
          <para>
            <text>Hon Trevor Mallard</text>
          </para>
          <para>
            <text>Sue Moroney</text>
          </para>
          <para>
            <text>David Shearer (from 18 November 2009)</text>
          </para>
          <para>
